{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_continental_ver02/data/sn84026749/00294557830/1914010101/0008.xml":{"full_text":"-aT'4rBe!4\"\"s\"-J'''\"\"1Tf\nTHE WASHINGTON TBIES, THURSDAY, JANUARY 1, 1914.\nI' i-\nCAPITAL TANGOES\nINDIANIAN GIVES A\nCHEERING MESSAGE\nTHE NEW YEAR 111\nHilarity Reigns in Dance Halls\nand Hotel Ball Rooms As\nMorning Hours Come.\nTn home and hostelrj Washington\n\"tangoed and \"hesltationed\" in tho\nJfew Tear.\" Despite the extra hour\ngranted by the new excise law less than\nthe ordinary number of arrests for\ntCtorfication were made during the cel-\nc-bratlon. J\nWashington celebrated with more\nenergy and as much hilarity as ever.\nMore corks, restaurateurs say today,\ntfere \"popped\" than in any other New\nTear celebration. The dance worked\nwonders for the celebration in this\ncity, as well tin in New York and else\nwhere, where the new steps which in\noculated humanity in 1913 were used\nalmost exclusively In the welcome ac\ncorded to the baby year.\n\"Hangovers.\" of course, are in order\nIn many places toda. Resolutions ore\ntoo. Buttermilk, it is said, is the pop-1\nuiar oeverasc. at one ui me iwami\nhotels and the \"morning after\" seltzer\nshowed a bull movement.\nWhile there were thousands who cele\nbrated -with wine and song and dance\nthere were, still other thousands who\nwelcomed \"the advent of the year by\nwatch night services in the churches\nin a spirit of devption.\nThen there were those of the attic\nBallroom variety, of the little two-by-fours\nwith single lights to chase away\nthe gloom who took to the street? to Go\ntheir merrymaking with the throngs of\nproinenaders, noticeably smaller in num\nbers than ever before. All said anc\ndone, it was a celebration in which\nmost oT \"Washington \"tangoed\" the year\nin, even the element -which usually\npromenade!) between midnight and the\n\"wee sma' hours\" taking to the dance\nhalls.\nHumor at the Hotels.\nCrowding the spacious ballrooms of\nthe Willard and Raleigh, hundreds of\ndancers tripped the, light fantastic until\nafter 2 a. m. They supped for the most\npart when they were compelled to do so\nby the retreat of the orchestras from\nthe dance halls to the supper rooms. At\nthe Shorebatn, the Powhatan, the Contl\npental, the Ebbitt House. Harvey's, the\nOccidental, and other hotels specially\nplanned celebrations were participated\ntn by capacity crowds.\nPeacock Alley at the Willard was the\ntceno of much exuberance. Old and\nfroung alike Joined hands, strangers\ngreeting each other as if they had been\nlonr-lost brothers and sisters.\nAn elderly man of silver locks, said\ny some to be a retired -naval officer,\ncaused considerable merriment bv in\nJormlng a pretty girl within the hear\ning of scores that he had loved her for\n''yeans and yeans.\"\n\"Why, Admiral, I've only known you\nCl few moments,\" replied the maid\nbashfully.\n\"Makes no difference,\"' replied the\nChesterfield.\nReplete with humorous incidents were\nthe final hours of the old and the first\nhours of the new year in the lobbies,\ncorridors, and dining-rooms of the ho-\nI\nIf- ffl\nf 2& i\nm lT xt 4 v\nvi Zs3iHfH\nI fm\nB OUTLOOK\nIL\nBRGHT\nTrade Leaders in All Sections\nLook For an Early Return of\nProsperity.\nCHARLES B. LANDIS,\nFormer Congressman Faces the New\nYear with optimism, and gives a\ncheering message to young men. i He\nsays opportunity to win success in\nlife is far more common today that\nit was in the early days of the country.\ntels. None seemed to be wobbly on\ntheir understandings, though all seemed\neffervescing with good cheer.\nGerman Societies Celebrate.\nThere were celebrations at the rooms\nof the Washington Saengerbund and the\nArion Society, where dances were held.\nThese dances lasted until the early\nmorning hours.\nOne of the most enjoyable entertain\nments in the city was \"Two Tears of\nVaudeville\" at the National Press Club.\nMany stars from the various theaters\ndropped In during the hours preceding\nand after 'midnight and entertained with\n\"stunts.\" Hundreds of members of the\nclub and their friends assembled for tho\nfun.\nNEW TORK, Jan. 1. General opti\nmism for 1914, confidence in the new\ncurrency law, and the belief that the\nIndustries of the country will adjust\nthemselves to the new tariff, was ex\npressed by business leaders today in\nevery part of the country. Telegrams\nreceived by the World from all sections\nof the Union and published today\nshowed that the conditions arc regarded\nas sound.\n\"The outlook for 1914 is bright,\" wired\nWilliam C. Redfield, Secretary of Com\nmerce. \"I think the fundamental eco\nnomic conditions .of the country arc\nsound.\"\nOther telegrams were, in part:\n\"If the currency law proves to be all\nthat the Administration at Washington\nhopes for it, and if the banks of the\ncountry, both national and State, will\nlargely and willingly adopt it, general\nconfidence will be restored and prosper\nity be re-cstabllshed.\"-James B. For\ngan. President First National. Bank,\nChicago.\n\"Our people are organizing a splendid\ncampaign for industrial expansion and\nextensoln of foreign trade. Los An\ngeles halls the New Year with charac\nteristic confidence.\" Arthur W. Kinney,\nPresident Los Angeles cnamDer ot\nCommerce.\n\"The outlook of Texas for 1914 Is bet\nter than any in her history.\" C W.\nHobson. president Dallas Chamber of\nCommerce.\n\"In this part of Michigan, and in\ngeneral, taking Into consideration the\nnew currency law and the new tariff\nlaw, to use a time-worn phrase,, I ilo\nnot see a single cloud on the horizon.\"\nJames Cousens, president Detroit\nBoard of Commerce.\n\"I feel that, disregarding unusual\ntroubles, the outlook is very, bright.\nThe financial skies have greatly clear\ned.\" William Guggenheim.\n\"I believe nothing can. prevent iabun\ndant prosperity .for the- entire country\nduring 1914.\" J.v Itt Arnold, \"president\nUtyc Kock., Ark., Chamber of Com\nmerce. \"Barring crop disasters, I predict the\nyear 1914 will bo one of the most pros\nperous we have had for many years.\"\nJohn D. Mcssmore, president St. Louis\nMerchants' Exchange.\n\"With the prospect of bountirul crops\nthe coming season, the continued pros\nrerltv of. Omaha and Nebraska is well\nnssuredV'i-George O. Kelly, president\nOrcaha Commercial Club,\n\"It la my opinion that early tn 1914\nthero will be a material Improvement\nin general business conditions as com\npared with the last half of 1913.\"-C. OT\nHance. president IndlanapollB Chamber\nof Commerce.\n\"We have nothing\" but optimism -to\nrecord as to the outlook for 1914.\"' Rob\nert Newton .Lynch, vice president han\nFrancisco Chamber of Cemmerce.\n\"The Northwest ia in splendid condi\ntion.\" W. J. McCabte, president Duluth\nBoard of Trade.\n\"The Boston Chamber of Commerce\nbelieves the outlook, for 1914 a favorable\none.\" James I. starrow, president Bos\ntcn Chamber of Commerce.\nElks Entertain At\nNew Year Eve Party\nTaking a happy leave of the old year\nand merrily hailing the new, members\nof tho Washington LodgcNo. 15. B. P.\nO. E., with their wives, families, friends\nand special guests, enjoyed a \"watch\nuartv Wednesday night at Elks' home.\n319 II street northwest. When the mid-\ntl, 1nA n? Hl\nmsni nour was Birutu, uie f,i\"o\nmultitude of lights Went out In a wink,\nand from basement to roof; the building\nwas in darkness. xnen, on mo whus\nof each room flashed out bright electric\nsigns with his greeting: \"Washington\nIiodce of Elks wishes you all a happy\nand prosperous New Year.\nAll merrymaWng was abruptly halted\nat 11 o'clock, while Past Exalted .Ruler\nFrank A. Kldd announced the Elks' 11\no'clock toast\nThe United States Marine Hand, with\nArthur Whltcomb as cornet soloist, gave\na special musical program. Contributing\nto the entertainment were Miss Clara\nNeacker. Prof. Horton. Fnnk Dough\nerty, Master Charles Hutchinson. Frank\nC. Green. Master Robert SchmCdt, Prof.\nMcGulre. Prof. Zimmerman and Milton\nDavis.\nRUDOLPH PREDICTS\nPROSPER 91 4\nin\nBoard, of Trade President,\nNew Year Message, Sees\nOnly Good Cheer.\ntelligence, charity and public spirited'\nness.\n\"The Maklnr of. a. Model Cllv\" will nl.\nways be the aim ot civic organizations\nIn Washington, and 1914 fs expected to\ndo much to help bring this about The\nBoard of Trade Is mapping out a cam\npaign for the improvement of 'Washing\nton, and. with a membership greater\nman tne ooara nas ever naa in tne past,\nmuch can bo done toward the establish\nment of a model city'\nArkansas BidsAdieu\nTo Last \"Wet\" Year\nPittsburgh Awakens\nLate With Hevy Head\nI ITTSBURGH, Jan. 1. Pittsburgh\nawoke late today and with a. heavy-hi-atf,\nas -a result of its midnight cele\nbration. While \"Billy\" Sunday held 15,\n000 at a? watch meeting in the Taber\nnacle, large crowds paraded the streets.\nThousands tangoed in the New Year at\na. score of large dances.\nStart 1 91 4 by Saving Money I\nBest Wishes\nfor a\nVery Happy\nNew Year\n'Mayer Bros. Co.\n937-939 F St.\nBrimful of optimism and confident of\nthe certain progress of Washington dur\ning vthe year 1914, was the New Year\nstatement Issued today by Cuno H. Ru\ndolph, president of the Board of Trade!\n\"Wtf all look confidently into, the new\nyear with a feeling that there will be\nmore prosperity for every one. The fina\npassage 'of tho curency law has served\nmaterially to clear the atmosphere\nfinancially and commercially throughout\nthe -country, and. confidence Is being\nspeedily restored.\n\"Washington will enjoy with the coun\ntry a prosperity which Is Inevitable\n.from the vast resources as a nation that\nthis country possesses.\n\"Civic movements for Improvement In\nWashington -will bo willingly supported,\nfor our community ranks high for in-'\ntLITTLE ROCK. Axk., Jan. J. Walls,\nmoans, and sighs from bibulous convi\nvials, marked die ushering in of the\nNew Year here,- for'at midnight the lid\nwas put on and clamped -when the law\nwhich \"made Arkansas practically a\n\"dry\" State, went into effect.\nVast stores of liquors, enough, to see\nthe nfght through, werw ordered in the\ndying- hours of 1913 as hosts of 1914 pre\npared to see him several damp hours\non the -way.\nCleveland's Sane New Year.\nCLEVELAND Jan. 1.-Clcveland gare\nthe New Year .a \"community greeting.\"\nTwelve bands. Including a total of 2S0\nmusicians, -were massed in the public\nsquare. To an audience of thousands\nthey played \"America.\" \"Onward. Chri-\ntlan Soldiers,\" \"The Star Spangled Ban\nner.\" \"Auid xang Syne,\" and other\nsongs.\nm\ni\nM RECORD\nIndiscreet Participants in'Cele-\noration Pay Over $349.\nSome Go to Jail:\neach In payment for their .release after\nbeing .arrested, for street walking.\nThe greatest 'number of arrests' oj\npersonar who werer sufficiently weaim?\nto gain their liberty by cash, deposit\nwas in the First precinct, where' seven\nIntoxicated and three -dlsorderlr per-'\nsons put up ball bonds.\nIt cost Washlngtonlans $349 to welcome\nthe New' Year to the accompanlmeat of\nnoise and alcoholic \"hilarity. In fines\nand forfeited ball bonds in the Polloa\nCourt today forty offend\"ers tnrlched the\nmsmct nnances fnat sum, and Finan\ncial Clerk. Adklns points to the receipts\nas greater than on any previous New\nxear. in 1910 tne nnes totaled only st\nwhile .this year's receipts exceed last\nyears total hy exactly J14L\n'In addition to the cosh receipts,\ntwenty persons who were either drunk\nor disorderly went to Jail In default ot\ncash fines.\nThirteen persons forfeited the sum ot\n$10 for intoxication; eighteen deposited\n$5 each for their release after arrest\nfor disorderly conduct and violations\nof tho traffic regulations; four were\ntaxed $1 each for minor disturbances\nin welcoming the- New Year with horns\nand .pistols, and three were penalized C\ni eacn jor lauing to nave rear lights on\n1 tnetl- nllfsiTrifiHtlA Twa j..iii... t.M n\n-\".-'.v-. A 1. U l411f ICtb wV'\nRadio Engineers to\nHear Expert Lecture\nRecent long distance experiments in\nwireless telegraphy will be explained\nby Dr. I w. Austin, radio- expert of\nthe Navy Department, at a meeting of\nthe Washington section, of the Institute\not Radio Engineers, next Wednesday\nevening In the physics building of th\nbureau of standards.\nMost members of- the section are\nwireless experts In the Government ser\nVice.\nFranz Josefs Many Gratings.\nVIENNA,. Jan. 1. Entering upon his\nsixty-sixth year as Emperor of Aus\ntria, Franz Josef, eighty-three years\nor age, today received more New Year\ngreetings probably than any ruler in\nthe world. Telegrams and cablegram,\npoured in upon the Emperor all day\nfrom every corn- of the world. Includ\ning a hearty dispatch from President\nWilson. Aside from the dispatches.\nthere was steady stream of callers.\nIncluding- bis daughters. Archduchess\nGisola and Princess Leooold of Bavaria.\ntheir children and grandchildren. For\neign Minister Berchtold, ambassadors\nof foreign powers, generals, admirals;\nand other high military officers.\nCo,\non High-Grade Groceries\nat Our EcMomy Stores\nWINTER\nCLOTHES\nWear Them While YouVe\nPaying for Them\nA Most Com\nplete Stock of\nStylish Clothes for\nMen, Women.\nBoys, and Chil\ndren, including all\nthe fashionable\nMillinery crea-\ntions and smart\nu e n 1 8 Furnish\nings. Our goods are of\nthe best quality\nand are offered at\nthe easiest terms\n,and at prices as\nlow as cash nrlces\nelsewhere.\nD. ROSENTHAL\n900 9th Street N.W.\nCor. 8th and lijc Sta.\nOpen Until 9 1'. M.\n113\ny\nI\nICpMS\nWf40s\nYour Feet\nvs.\nGeorges\nThere are many aches and pains\ndne to bad feet, but as yet We\nhate failed to encounter a cue\nthat Tre could not conquer. If\n\"yon' are a victim of trouble\nHome feet. let u warn you now\nthat you are Jeopardlzlni; your\ngeneral condition and health. Let\nus correct your foot troubles.\nGet Bid of Tour\nCorns, Bunions,\nGallons Places,\nIngrowing Nails,\nFiat Foot, &c\nCO.VSUITATIO.V FHEE\nCHILBLAINS will And an en\nemy ia 